LONGEST SUBSTRING WITHOUT REPEATING CHARACTERS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Given a string s, return the length of the longest substring
without repeating characters.


EXAMPLE 1
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Input:  s = "abcabcbb"
Output: 3
Explanation: "abc"


EXAMPLE 2
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Input:  s = "bbbbb"
Output: 1


EXAMPLE 3
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Input:  s = "pwwkew"
Output: 3
Explanation: "wke"


CONSTRAINTS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
0 <= s.length <= 5 * 10^4
s consists of English letters, digits, symbols and spaces.


APPROACH — SLIDING WINDOW + FREQUENCY ARRAY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Use two pointers (first, second)
• Expand second pointer
• If duplicate found → shrink from first
• Track maximum window size

Time  Complexity : O(n)
Space Complexity : O(1)


class Solution {
public:
    int lengthOfLongestSubstring(string s) {

        int first = 0;
        int second = 0;
        int len = 0;

        vector<bool> count(256,0);

        while(second < s.size())
        {
            while(count[s[second]])
            {
                count[s[first]] = 0;
                first++;
            }

            count[s[second]] = 1;
            len = max(len, second-first+1);
            second++;
        }

        return len;
    }
};
